<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(disclaimer: I can't verify the following--its mosty personal theory and opinion gained from &quot;touchy feely&quot; observation, not empirical data)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Success rate in channelling is inversely proportional to the level of the spell being cast, in my observations.<br>
<br>
Since rangers (and many other classes, in fact) routinely use lower level spells than their current max, they tend to observe better channeling success than wizards.  Wizards tend to use higher level spells in many channeling situations, and thus appear to be worse channellers.<br>
<br>
For example, my Shaman channels Togor's like a champ.  The spell is several spell ranks below his current max.  He clearly channels it much more succesfully than my Arcanist channel SoS, which is exactly at his max spell rank.<br>
<br>
Yeah, fluffy at best, but its a theory.  Also explains how enchanters in AE groups could channel those low level AE stun spells through a severe beat-down, while I was lucky to crank out a Jyll's if I'd taken more than a couple hits.<br>
